Introduction¶

This document explores the U.S. Department of Transportation (U.S.DOT) dataset of 2007 flights in the United States. This dataset provides information about airline on-time performance and flight delays. It is based on data filed by airlines each month with the Department of Transportation’s Bureau of Transportation Statistics (Office of Airline Information), as described in 14 CFR Part 234 of DOT's regulations. It covers non stop scheduled-service flights between points within the United States (including territories) by the nineteen (19) U.S. air carriers that have at least one percent of total domestic scheduled-service passenger revenues, and the two (2) carriers that reported flight delay data voluntarily during 2007.

The goal of this project is to conduct an exploratory data analysis on the flights dataset in order to figure out which features are more related to a flight delay.

A flight is counted as "on time" if it operated less than 15 minutes after the scheduled time shown in the carriers' Computerized Reservations Systems (CRS), according to U.S.DOT. The delay analysis in this project will focus on arrival delays, specifically A+15 (arrival at the gate within 15 minutes after scheduled arrival), as that is the measure that the U.S.DOT reports.

General Properties¶

Before moving forward, let's describe each of the columns of the gathered dataframe:

  • Year: Year of the flight. [int64]
  • Month: Month of the flight (1-12). [int64]
  • DayofMonth: Day of the Month of the flight (1-31). [int64]
  • DayOfWeek: Number representing the Day of the Week. 1 (Monday) - 7 (Sunday). [int64]
  • DepTime: Actual Departure Time - local time: hhmm. [float64]
  • CRSDepTime: Scheduled Departure Time - local time: hhmm. [int64]
  • ArrTime: Actual Arrival Time - local time: hhmm. [float64]
  • CRSArrTime: Scheduled Arrival Time - local time: hhmm. [int64]
  • DepDelay: Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual departure time. Early departures show negative numbers. [float64]
  • ArrDelay: Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual arrival time. Early arrivals show negative numbers. [float64]
  • UniqueCarrier: Unique Carrier Code. When the same code has been used by multiple carriers, a numeric suffix is used for earlier users, for example, PA, PA(1), PA(2). [object]
  • FlightNum: Flight number. [int64]
  • TailNum: Plane tail number. [object]
  • ActualElapsedTime: Actual Elapsed Time (time computed from gate departure time to gate arrival time) of Flight, in Minutes. [float64]
  • CRSElapsedTime: Scheduled Elapsed Time (time computed from gate departure time to gate arrival time) of Flight, in Minutes. [float64]
  • AirTime: Actual Flight Time (time computed from the moment an aircraft leaves the ground until it touches the ground at the end of a flight stage), in Minutes. [float64]
  • TaxiIn: Actual Taxi In Time, in Minutes. For arriving flights, is the period between the Landing Time and the In-Block Time. [int64]
  • TaxiOut: Actual Taxi Out Time, in Minutes. For departing flights, is the period between the Off-Block Time and the Take Off Time. [int64]
  • Origin: Origin IATA airport code. [object]
  • Dest: Destination IATA airport code. [object]
  • Distance: Distance between airports, in miles. [int64]
  • Cancelled: Cancelled Flight Indicator (1=Yes). [int64]
  • CancellationCode: Specifies The Reason For Cancellation (A = carrier, B = weather, C = NAS, D = security). [object]
  • Diverted: Diverted Flight Indicator (1=Yes). It indicates if a plane followed a different route or went to a different destination than they originally intended. [int64]
  • CarrierDelay: Carrier Delay as Cause of Delay, in Minutes. [int64]
  • WeatherDelay: Weather Delay as Cause of Delay, in Minutes. [int64]
  • NASDelay: National Air System Delay as Cause of Delay, in Minutes. [int64]
  • SecurityDelay: Security Delay as Cause of Delay, in Minutes. [int64]
  • LateAircraftDelay: Late Aircraft Delay as Cause of Delay, in Minutes. [int64]

Quality Issues

  • There are missing values in "CRSElapsedTime" and "ArrDelay" columns, when there should not be missing values in them.
  • All values in "Year" column are 2007, so we should drop this column.
  • We will not use "DepTime", "CRSDepTime", "ArrTime", "DepDelay", "TailNum", "ActualElapsedTime", "AirTime", "TaxiIn", "TaxiOut", "Cancelled", "CancellationCode", "Diverted", "CarrierDelay", "WeatherDelay", "NASDelay", "SecurityDelay" and "LateAircraftDelay" columns for our analysis, so we should drop them.
  • "DayOfWeek" values should be Monday-Sunday, instead of numbers. This column should be a categorical ordinal type.
  • There are 27 duplicated rows, these should be dropped.
  • "FlightNum" column should be string type instead of integer type because we will not perform mathematical operations with it.
  • "DayofMonth" column should be renamed to "DayOfMonth" to follow the other columns' pattern.
  • There is a negative value in "CRSElapsedTime" column, when it can only have positive values.

Feature Engineering

  • We need "CRSArrivalTime" column based on "CRSArrTime" column, but in hour ranges. It should be a category (ordinal) type. After the creation of "CRSArrivalTime" column, we should drop "CRSArrTime" column.
  • A "Delayed" column should be created, based on whether it had a late arrival time or not (according to "ArrDelay" values). It should be a Boolean type. After the creation of "Delayed" column, we should drop "ArrDelay" column.
  • We need a "Route" column, based on the airport of origin and destination.
  • A "Weekday_Weekend" column is needed based on "DayOfWeek" values.

Feature Engineering¶

To answer some of our questions and to get a deeper understanding of our data, there are variables we need to create from other existing columns. In the next cells, we will be proceding with that.

#1: We need "CRSArrivalTime" column based on "CRSArrTime" column, but in hour ranges. It should be a category (ordinal) type. After the creation of "CRSArrivalTime" column, we should drop "CRSArrTime" column.

Define¶

  • Use pandas.cut to create hour range based on "CRSArrTime" column values and input those values into a new column called "CRSArrivalTime".
  • Drop "CRSArrTime" column.

Code¶

In [46]:
# Let's create 'CRSArrivalTime' column
bin_edges = list(range(0,2500,100))
labels = ['0 AM','1 AM','2 AM','3 AM','4 AM','5 AM','6 AM','7 AM','8 AM','9 AM',
          '10 AM','11 AM','12 PM','1 PM','2 PM','3 PM','4 PM','5 PM','6 PM','7 PM',
          '8 PM','9 PM','10 PM','11 PM']
df_clean['CRSArrivalTime'] = pd.cut(df_clean['CRSArrTime'], bin_edges, right=False, include_lowest=True, labels=labels)

Storing¶

Let's store our df_clean table in a CSV file.

In [67]:
df_clean.to_csv('cleaned_dataset.csv', index=False)

Before proceding with EDA, let's describe each of the columns of the final df_clean:

  • Month: Month of the flight (1-12). [integer]
  • DayOfMonth: Day of the Month of the flight (1-31). [integer]
  • DayOfWeek: Day of the Week (Monday - Sunday). [category]
  • UniqueCarrier: Unique Carrier Code. [string]
  • FlightNum: Flight number. [string]
  • CRSElapsedTime: Scheduled Elapsed Time (time computed from gate departure time to gate arrival time) of Flight, in Minutes. [float]
  • Origin: Origin IATA airport code. [string]
  • Dest: Destination IATA airport code. [string]
  • Distance: Distance between airports, in miles. [integer]
  • CRSArrivalTime: Scheduled Arrival Time, local time, in hourly range. [category]
  • Delayed: If the flight is delayed or not. Delayed means the flight arrived equal or greater than 15 minutes after scheduled arrival time. [boolean]
  • Route: Route of the flight, with origin and departure airport. [string]
  • Weekday_Weekend: If day of the flight was during weekday or weekend. [string]

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

There are 7,275,259 flights in the cleaned dataset with 13 features. Most variables are qualitative in nature.

  • Quantitative columns: "CRSElapsedTime", "Distance".
  • Qualitative columns: "Month", "DayOfMonth", "DayOfWeek", "UniqueCarrier", "FlightNum", "Origin", "Dest", "CRSArrivalTime", "Delayed", "Route", "Weekday_Weekend".

What is the main feature of interest in the dataset?¶

We are most interested in figuring out what features are more related to a flight delay.

What features in the dataset do we think will help support the investigation into the feature of interest?¶

We expect that delays are more related to time factors like "Month", "DayOfMonth", "DayOfWeek", "Weekday_Weekend" and "CRSArrivalTime". But we also think other factors related to the flight, like "UniqueCarrier", "CRSElapsedTime", "Route" and "Distance", could be related to the delay of flights.

# Let's define a new function for Bar Chart with mean value displayed and labels in each bar
def func_bar1(X, Y, title, xlabel, ylabel, text_x, text_y, mean, meanlabel,rotation=0):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,7))
    
    plt.bar(np.arange(len(X)),Y,color='lightblue')
    
    plt.xticks(np.arange(len(X)), X, rotation=rotation)
    plt.title(title, fontweight="bold")
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    ax.get_yaxis().set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: format(int(x), ',')))
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel, labelpad=10)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel, labelpad=15)
    for i,v in enumerate(Y):
        if Y.dtypes == "int64":
            ax.text(i - text_x, v + text_y, '{:,.0f}'.format(v), color='blue')
        else:
            ax.text(i - text_x, v + text_y,'{:,.2f}'.format(v), color='blue')
    if mean is not None and meanlabel is not None:
        plt.hlines(mean, xmin=-0.4, xmax=len(X)-0.6, linestyles='dashed', label=meanlabel, color='grey')
        ax.text(len(X) - 0.6 - text_x, mean + text_y*2,'{:,.2f}'.format(mean), color='black')
        plt.legend()
    return plt.show();

# Let's define the function for Boxplot of Quantitative Values

def func_box(X, var_name, xlabel, decimal=0):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,6))
    bp = plt.boxplot(X, vert=False, showmeans=True)
    plt.title('Boxplot of {}'.format(var_name), fontweight="bold")
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.yticks([1],["Boxplot"], rotation=90, verticalalignment="center")
    ax.grid(b=True, axis='x')
    ax.get_xaxis().set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: format(int(x), ',')))
    # Adding mean label
    if abs(X.mean() - X.median()) < 0.1:
        ax.text(X.mean(), 1.02, '%.2f' %(X.mean()),color='green')
    elif abs(X.mean() - X.median()) < 1:
        ax.text(X.mean(), 1.02, '%.1f' %(X.mean()),color='green')
    else:
        ax.text(X.mean(), 1.02, '%.0f' %(X.mean()),color='green')
    
    # Adding median label
    x, y = bp['medians'][0].get_xydata()[1] 
    if abs(X.mean() - X.median()) < 0.1:
        ax.text(x, y+0.01, '%.2f' % x, horizontalalignment='center')
    elif abs(X.mean() - X.median()) < 1:
        ax.text(x, y+0.01, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center')
    else:
        ax.text(x, y+0.01, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center')
    
    if decimal == 0:
        # Adding quantiles labels
        x, y = bp['boxes'][0].get_xydata()[0]
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')
        x, y = bp['boxes'][0].get_xydata()[3] 
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')

        # Adding whiskers labels
        x, y = bp['caps'][0].get_xydata()[0]
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')
        x, y = bp['whiskers'][1].get_xydata()[1] 
        ax.text(x,y-0.05, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')

    else:
        # Adding quantiles labels
        x, y = bp['boxes'][0].get_xydata()[0]
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')
        x, y = bp['boxes'][0].get_xydata()[3] 
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')

        # Adding whiskers labels
        x, y = bp['caps'][0].get_xydata()[0]
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')
        x, y = bp['whiskers'][1].get_xydata()[1] 
        ax.text(x,y-0.05, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top') 
                
    return plt.show();

# Let's define the function for Histograms of Quantitative Continuous Values

def func_hist(x,var_name, xlabel,ylabel):
    fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,8))
    plt.hist(x, bins='auto')
    plt.title('Histogram of {}'.format(var_name), fontweight="bold")
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    ax.set_xlim(0,)
    ax.set_ylim(0,)
    ax.get_yaxis().set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: format(int(x), ',')))
    return plt.show();

It's importat to notice that we chose the "auto" method to select the number of bins of histograms. These auto method chooses the maximum number of bins between the "Sturges" and "Freedman Diaconis" estimators.

# Let's define the function for Boxplot with Log Scale in the X axis

def func_box_log(X, var_name, xlabel, decimal=0):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16.5,6))
    bp = plt.boxplot(X, vert=False, showmeans=True)
    plt.title('Boxplot of {}'.format(var_name), fontweight="bold")
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.yticks([1],["Boxplot"], rotation=90, verticalalignment="center")
    ax.grid(b=True, axis='x')
    plt.xscale('log')
    # Adding mean label
    if abs(X.mean() - X.median()) < 0.1:
        ax.text(X.mean(), 1.02, '%.2f' %(X.mean()),color='green')
    elif abs(X.mean() - X.median()) < 1:
        ax.text(X.mean(), 1.02, '%.1f' %(X.mean()),color='green')
    else:
        ax.text(X.mean(), 1.02, '%.0f' %(X.mean()),color='green')
    
    # Adding median label
    x, y = bp['medians'][0].get_xydata()[1] 
    if abs(X.mean() - X.median()) < 0.1:
        ax.text(x, y+0.01, '%.2f' % x, horizontalalignment='center')
    elif abs(X.mean() - X.median()) < 1:
        ax.text(x, y+0.01, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center')
    else:
        ax.text(x, y+0.01, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center')
    
    if decimal == 0:
        # Adding quantiles labels
        x, y = bp['boxes'][0].get_xydata()[0]
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')
        x, y = bp['boxes'][0].get_xydata()[3] 
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')

        # Adding whiskers labels
        x, y = bp['caps'][0].get_xydata()[0]
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')
        x, y = bp['whiskers'][1].get_xydata()[1] 
        ax.text(x,y-0.05, '%.0f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')

    else:
        # Adding quantiles labels
        x, y = bp['boxes'][0].get_xydata()[0]
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')
        x, y = bp['boxes'][0].get_xydata()[3] 
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')

        # Adding whiskers labels
        x, y = bp['caps'][0].get_xydata()[0]
        ax.text(x,y-0.01, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top')
        x, y = bp['whiskers'][1].get_xydata()[1] 
        ax.text(x,y-0.05, '%.1f' % x, horizontalalignment='center', verticalalignment='top') 
                
    return plt.show();

Let's discuss the distribution of the variable of interest.¶

The "delayed" variable is a Boolean, with an unbalance towards the negative (not delayed). This was not a surprise because most airlines report time-related KPIs to the aviation authorities and airports in order to keep their operations.

Of the features investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Were there any operations needed to be performed on the data to tidy, adjust, or change its form?¶

  • The distribution of flights by "Month" had an outlier in February (a very low value).
  • The distribution of flights per "Day of Week" also had an outlier in Saturday (very low value).
  • Regarding the distribution of Flights based on Scheduled Arrival Time (per hour), we could also spot a clear flight reduction between 0 AM and 6 AM (inclusive).
  • We also discovered that a same Flight Number could have different origins, destinations and routes.
  • On the other hand, Atlanta's Hartsfield-Jackson (ATL) airport does not appear in the Top 10 Route despite being the Top Airport as origin and destination.
  • Lastly, we needed to perform a log10 transformation on "Destination" and "CRSElapsedTime" axes, because with their natural units their distributions were right skewed.

All the above is something to keep an eye out for the rest of the analysis.

# Let's define a function for stacked bar chart, with absolute counts

def func_stack_bar_abs(df, cat1_order, cat2_order, cat_var1, cat_var2, ylabel):
    baselines = np.zeros(len(cat1_order))
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))
    plt.xlabel(cat_var1)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title('Stacked bar chart, with absolute counts')
    # for each second-variable category:
    for i in range(len(cat2_order)):
        # isolate the counts of the first category,
        cat2 = cat2_order[i]
        inner_counts = df[df[cat_var2] == cat2][cat_var1].value_counts()
        # then plot those counts on top of the accumulated baseline
        plt.bar(x = np.arange(len(cat1_order)), height = inner_counts[cat1_order],bottom = baselines)
        baselines += inner_counts[cat1_order]
    ax.get_yaxis().set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: format(int(x), ',')))
    plt.xticks(np.arange(len(cat1_order)), cat1_order)
    plt.legend(cat2_order, title = cat_var2);

# Let's define a function for stacked bar chart, with relative frequency

def func_stack_bar_per(df, cat1_order, cat2_order, cat_var1, cat_var2, ylabel, rotation=0):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))
    plt.xlabel(cat_var1)
    ax.set_xlabel(cat_var1, labelpad=10)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title('Stacked bar chart, with relative frequency')
    artists = [] # for storing references to plot elements
    baselines = np.zeros(len(cat1_order))
    cat1_counts = df[cat_var1].value_counts()

    # for each second-variable category:
    for i in range(len(cat2_order)):
        # isolate the counts of the first category,
        cat2 = cat2_order[i]
        inner_counts = df[df[cat_var2] == cat2][cat_var1].value_counts()
        inner_props = inner_counts / cat1_counts
        # then plot those counts on top of the accumulated baseline
        bars = plt.bar(x = np.arange(len(cat1_order)),
                       height = inner_props[cat1_order],
                       bottom = baselines)
        artists.append(bars)
        baselines += inner_props[cat1_order]
        
        for r in bars:
            h = r.get_height()
            plt.text(r.get_x() + r.get_width()/2., h/1.5, '{:,.2f}'.format(h), ha="center", color="white") 

            
    plt.xticks(np.arange(len(cat1_order)), cat1_order, rotation=rotation)
    plt.legend(reversed(artists), reversed(cat2_order), framealpha = 1,
               bbox_to_anchor = (1, 0.5), loc = 6, title = cat_var2);

#10: What is the distribution of Delayed flight vs Distance between airports?

In [186]:
# Let's define a function for a violinplot and a boxplot
def func_violin_box(df, cat_var, num_var):
    # upper plot: violin plot
    plt.figure(figsize = [16, 5])
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
    ax1 = sns.violinplot(data = df, x = num_var, y = cat_var, orient='h', inner = None);

    # lower plot: box plot
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
    sns.boxplot(data = df, x = num_var, y = cat_var, orient='h')
    plt.xlim(ax1.get_xlim());
In [187]:
# Let's plot a violinplot and a boxplot of 'Delayed' and 'Distance' columns

In [188]:
# Let's define a function for a violinplot and a boxplot with log-scale in x axis
def func_violin_box_log(df, cat_var, num_var):
    # upper plot: violin plot
    plt.figure(figsize = [16, 5])
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
    ax1 = sns.violinplot(data = df, x = num_var, y = cat_var, orient='h', inner = None)
    plt.xscale('log');

    # lower plot: box plot
    plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
    sns.boxplot(data = df, x = num_var, y = cat_var, orient='h')
    plt.xscale('log')
    plt.xlim(ax1.get_xlim())
    plt.xlabel('Log10 of ' + num_var);
In [189]:
# Let's plot a violinplot and a boxplot of 'Delayed' and log10 of 'Distance'
func_violin_box_log(df_clean, 'Delayed', 'Distance')

We can see that after a log transformation in Distance, the distribution for both delayed and not delayed flights becomes less right skewed. However, there are still a lot of high-values in both.

#12: What is the distribution of flights per day of each month?

In [194]:
# Let's plot a histogram of amount of flights per day facetted by month

In the facetted histogram above we see that there is no clear pattern in the amount of flights per day of month among all months. However, this analysis could be expanded by adding a variable of weekday and weekend in the multivariate analysis.

Let's talk about some of the relationships we observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Even though the percentage of delays per month follows a somewhat uniform distribution, there was a notable increment in the percentage of delayed flights during December 2007.
  • Even though the percentage of delays per day of week follows a somewhat uniform distribution, Friday had the highest percent of the week.
  • We also noticed a spike in the percent of delays per hour between 9 PM and 0 AM (inclusive), and a notable reduction in the percent of delays at 7 AM.

  • We also noticed how the amount of flights of a Carrier, Origin and Destination Airport is related to its delay in flights. For example:

    • Hawaiian Airlines and Aloha Airlines have the fewest operations in our clean dataset and the lowest percent of late arrivals.
    • Charles B. Wheeler Downtown Airport (MKC) and Mid-Delta Airport (GLH), as destination airports, did not have delayed flights in 2007 but their flights operations as destination were less than 3.
    • Mid-Delta Airport (GLH), as origin airport, did not have flights arriving late to their destinations, but its flight operations as origin was less than 3.

    This could have suggested that a low operation is easier to handle in terms of quality of service (Arrival delay). However, there were exceptions that proved the opposite:

    • Charles B. Wheeler Downtown Airport (MKC) had all of their flights arriving late to their destination. But, this is because its one single flight arrived late to its destination.
    • Southwest Airlines (WN) is in our Top 4 ranking (of lowest percent of late operations), having the highest amount of annual operations in our clean dataset.

  • Following the IQR criteria:

    • All of the Destination Airports of our Worst 10 and Top 10 rankings (based on the percent of late operations) were outliers.
    • 10 Origin Airports of our Worst 10 ranking (with the highest percent of late arrivals to their destination) were outliers.
    • 7 Origin Airports of the Top 10 (with the lowest percent of late arrivals to their destination) were also outliers.
    • 11 Flight Numbers of our Worst 11 ranking (with the highest percent of late operations) were outliers
    • 83 Routes, with all of their operations delayed, were outliers.
  • The distribution of Distance is pretty similar whether a flight was delayed or not.
  • The distribution of Scheduled Elapsed Time is pretty similar whether a flight was delayed or not

Were there any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature of interest)?¶

  • There is no clear pattern in the amount of flights per day of month among all months. However, this analysis could be expanded by adding a variable of weekday and weekend in the multivariate analysis.

In the facetted histogram above we can see that, in our clean dataset, the amount of flights per day of each month is mostly lower when it's a weekend than when it's a weekday. This could be because there are more business flights happening during weekdays than on weekends, or maybe weekdays' price is lower hence the increment of flights. However, since there is no information to confirm any of these hypotheses, further analsys should be made.

Let's talk about some of the relationships we observed in this part of the investigation.¶

  • The pattern observed in the bivariate analysis (the amount of delayed flights is always lower than the amount of not delayed flights throughout the months) mostly remains even when analyzing it on a multivariate level by scheduled arrival hour, day of month, day of week or weekday/weekend.
  • The amount of flights per month is directly related to the number of delayed flights per month when analyzing it by day of week, scheduled arrival hour or weekday/weekend. We didn’t see this pattern when analyzing the data per day of month per month, though.
  • The percent of delayed flights per month is directly related to the amount of delayed flights per month when analyzing it by day of month or day of week. We didn’t see this pattern repeating when analyzing the data per scheduled arrival hour per month or weekday/weekend, though.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  • The pattern of decreased flights between 0 AM and 6 AM (inclusive) from the bivariate analysis remains when analyzing it on a multivariate level by days of week and weekdays/weekends.
  • The amount of delayed flights is always lower than the amount of not delayed flights throughout the scheduled arrival hours when analyzing it by days of week or weekday/weekend.

Conclusions¶

Main insights
For our clean dataset (2007 domestic flights in United States reported by 21 carriers), we can conclude the following:

  • 24.8% of flights were delayed.
  • 73.4% of flights happened during weekdays.
  • Most of the flights (70% or more) were on time each month.
  • Most of the flights (70% or more) were on time each day of the week.
  • There is a clear flight reduction between 0 AM and 6 AM (inclusive), in annual terms.
  • There is a clear flight reduction between 0 AM and 6 AM (inclusive) throughout the months.
  • There is a clear flight reduction between 0 AM and 6 AM (inclusive) during both weekdays and weekends.
  • The preferred hours to flight are between 9 AM - 8 PM (inclusive).
  • The majority of Flights (between 25% and 75% percentile) had a Distance between airports between 320 and 948 miles.
  • The majority of Flights (between 25% and 75% percentile) had a Scheduled Elapsed Time between 78 and 157 minutes.
  • Southwest Airlines (WN) is the carrier who had the highest annual number of flights (even 2 times higher than the average amount of flights per carrier).
  • Atlanta's Hartsfield-Jackson (ATL) is the airport who had the highest annual number of flights as origin and destination (even 15 times higher than the average amount of flights per origin or destination).
  • "16" is the Flight Number who had the highest annual number of fligths (even 4 times higher than the average amount of flights per flight number).
  • KAHULUI HI (OGG) - HONOLULU HI (HNL) is the route who had the highest annual number of flights (even 15 times higher than the average amount of flights per route). The second route involves also those two airport but with the inverse order.
  • The majority of months (between 25% and 75% percentile) had a Percentage of Flight Delay between 21 and 28.7%.
  • The majority of days of the week (between 25% and 75% percentile) had a Percentage of Flight Delay between 23.2 and 26.3%.
  • The majority of Schedule Arrival hours (between 25% and 75% percentile) had a Percentage of Flight Delay between 19.2% and 31.5%.
  • The majority of Origin Airports (between 25% and 75% percentile) had between 8.7% and 36.2% of their flights arriving late to their destination.
  • The majority of Destination Airports (between 25% and 75% percentile) had a delayed in their arrival operations between 22.4% and 29.3%.
  • The majority of flight numbers (between 25% and 75% percentile) had a percent of late operations between 20.2% and 30.4%.
  • The majority of Routes (between 25% and 75% percentile) had a percent of late operations between 18% and 30.4%.
  • The majority of Delayed Flights (between 25% and 75%) had a Distance between 334 and 980 miles from origin to destination.
  • The majority of Delayed Flights (between 25% and 75%) had a Scheduled Elapsed Time between 80 and 160 minutes.
  • Weekdays and weekends both have a similar percent of delayed flights. Weekdays have a slight higher percentage than the average (5% above).
  • Hawaiian Airlines (HA) is the Carrier who had the lowest percent of late operations: 6.31%, which is 73% lower than the average percent of delay per carrier.
  • Atlantic Southeast Airlines (EV) is the Carrier who had the highest percent of late operations: 33.02%, which is 39% higher than the average percent of delay per carrier.
  • Most of the flights (65% or more) were on time each hour (Schedule Arrival Time).
  • There was a spike in the percent of delays per hour between 9 PM and 0 AM (inclusive), and a notable reduction in the percent of delays at 7 AM. The highest value (at 10 PM and 0 AM) was 39% above the mean and the lowest value (7 AM) was 53% below the mean.
  • Moore County Airport (SOP) is the airport with the worst percent of late arrival operations: 47.85%, 85% higher than the Average percent of late operations by Destination Airport.
  • The average arrival delay per origin airport is 22.98%.
  • The average arrival delay per destination airport is 25.84%.
  • The distribution of Distance is pretty similar whether a flight was delayed or not.
  • The distribution of Scheduled Elapsed Time is pretty similar whether a flight was delayed or not.
  • Saturday tends to have the lowest amount of flights per day of week in most of the months, with a mean of 76,302 flights per month.
  • The amount of flights per day of each month is mostly lower when it's a weekend than when it's a weekday.
  • On average, the percentage of delayed flights per day hits its lowest on September.
  • On average, 4,940 flights arrived late per day of each month, which is 67% lower than the average amount of flights that didn't arrive late per day of each month (14,991 flights).
  • On average, the percentage of delayed flights per day of week hits its lowest on Saturday through most of the months.
  • On average, the percentage of delayed flights per scheduled arrival hour hits its lowest at 7 AM for most days of week.
  • On average, the percentage of delayed flights per scheduled arrival hour hits its highest between 9 PM and 0 AM (inclusive) in most days of the week.
  • On average, the percentage of delayed flights per scheduled arrival hour hits its lowest at 7 AM through most of the months.
  • On average, the percentage of delayed flights is similar for both weekdays and weekends. However, the percentage of delayed flights is higher on weekdays in most of the months.
  • Out of the delayed flights per month, on average 76% of them happened on weekdays.
  • The pattern of decreased flights between 0 AM and 6 AM (inclusive) from the bivariate analysis remains when analyzing it on a multivariate level by days of week and weekdays/weekends.
  • The amount of delayed flights is always lower than the amount of not delayed flights throughout the scheduled arrival hours when analyzing it by days of week or weekday/weekend.
  • The amount of delayed flights on Saturday's is the lowest in most of the months, with a mean of 15,531 delayed flights per month.
  • The amount of delayed flights is the lowest between 1 AM - 4 AM (inclusive) every month, being 44 delayed flights the lowest average per hour.
  • The amount of delayed flights is always lower than the amount of not delayed flights throughout the months. This pattern mostly remains even when analyzing it on a multivariate level by scheduled arrival hour, day of month, day of week or weekday/weekend.

Other insights

  • Even though the percentage of delays per month follows a somewhat uniform distribution, there was a notable increment in the percentage of delayed flights during December 2007: 33% of flights were delayed that month, which is 34% higher than the average delay per month. Also, September 2007 has the lowest percent of delayed flights: only 17% of flights were delayed that month, which is 30% lower than the average delay per month.
  • Even though the percentage of delays per day of week follows a somewhat uniform distribution, Friday had the highest percent of the week: 28% of flights were delayed that day, which is 15% higher than the average delay per day of week.
  • Overall, the distribution of flights per month is uniform, with a mean of 606,272 flights per month. However, there is an outlier: February 2007 has way less flights than the rest of the months of 2007.
  • Overall, the distribution of flights per day of week is somewhat uniform, with a mean of 1,039,323 flights per day of week. However, there is an outlier: Saturday has way less flights than the rest of the days of the week.
  • Hawaiian Airlines and Aloha Airlines have the fewest operations in our clean dataset and the lowest percent of late arrivals. On the other hand, Southwest Airlines (WN) is also in our Top 4 ranking (of lowest percent of late operations), having the highest amount of annual operations in our clean dataset. This, in contrast with the other 2 previous airlines, shows how a carrier can excel in the quality of service despite having a massive amount of services.
  • 11 Flight Numbers had all of their flights delayed. But, 8 of them only had one single flight in the entire dataset, so that explains the high value (100%) despite the Average percent of late operations by Flight Number being only 25.89%.
  • The amount of flights that arrived late is always lower than the amount of flights that did not arrive late everyday of every month, with the exception of certain days in February and December.
  • The amount of delayed flights per day of week is always lower than the amount of not delayed flights per day of week throughout the months.
  • The amount of delayed flights per Scheduled Arrival Time (hour) is always lower than the amount of not delayed flights per Scheduled Arrival Time (hour) throughout the months.
  • The amount of delayed flights per Scheduled Arrival Time (hour) is always lower than the amount of not delayed flights per Scheduled Arrival Time (hour) throughout the days of week. We also see that the amount of delayed flights is the lowest between 1 AM - 4 AM (inclusive) every day of week, being 76 delayed flights the lowest average per hour.
  • The amount of delayed flights per Scheduled Arrival Time (hour) is always lower than the amount of not delayed flights per Scheduled Arrival Time (hour) in both weekdays and weekends.
  • There is a clear flight reduction between 0 AM and 6 AM (inclusive) throughout the days of week.
  • Weekdays have a higher amount of flights per month than weekends through all the months. We can also see that the amount of delayed flights is low during both weekends and weekdays throughout the months.
  • The percentage of delayed flights per scheduled arrival hour is similar for both weekdays and weekends. We see that, on average, between 8 AM and 0 AM (inclusive) the percent of delayed flights is higher for weekdays and between 1 AM and 7 AM (inclusive) the percent of delayed flights is higher for weekends.
  • Both weekdays and weekends have their lowest percentage of delayed flights at 7 AM, and their highest at 0 AM.
  • None of the Top 4 Carriers (based on the lowest percent of late operations) arrive to all Top 10 Airports (based on the highest amount of flights operation / arrivals). From the bivariate analysis we know that some of these airlines, like Hawaiian Airlines (HA) and Aloha Airlines (AQ), have few operations, so it is not surprising they don't arrive to all the airports. However, Southwest Airlines (WN) having the highest amount of annual operations does not arrive to all the Top 10 Airports, either.
  • A same Flight Number could have different origins, destinations and routes.
  • Atlanta's Hartsfield-Jackson airport (ATL) does not appear in the Top 10 Route (based on their annual number of operations) despite being the Top Airport (based on their annual number of operations) as origin and destination.
  • None of the highest-amount of operations Airports (as destination) is in the Worst 10 ranking. However, Gustavus Airport (GST) is in the Worst 10 ranking of Destination Airports with the highest percent of late arrival operations, despite its few operations as a destination airport.
  • Mid-Delta Airport (GLH), as origin airport, did not have flights arriving late to their destinations. Mid-Delta Airport (GLH) had so few operations, it is not surprising its percent of flights delay is zero.
  • Out of the origin airports with the lowest amount of operations, only GLH appears in the Top 10 Origin Airports with the lowest percent of flights that arrived late to their destinations.
  • Charles B. Wheeler Downtown Airport (MKC), as origin airport, had all of their flights arriving late to their destination. But, we noticed this is because its one single flight arrived late to its destination. Other three origin airports with the lowest amount of annual operation (PIR, GST, DLG) are also in this Worst 10 ranking of Origin Airports, with the highest percent of flights that arrived late to their destinations.
  • None of the Top 10 airports with the highest annual amount of operations (as origin) is in the Worst 10 ranking of Origin Airports with the highest percent of flights that arrived late to their destinations.
  • None of the Flight Numbers with the highest amount of operations were in the Worst 11 ranking of Flight Numbers, with the highest percent of late operations.
  • Charles B. Wheeler Downtown Airport (MKC) and Mid-Delta Airport (GLH) did not have delayed flights, as destination airports, in 2007. These two destinations had so few operations, it is not surprising their percent of flights delay is zero. Besides MKC and GLH, EAU (Chippewa Valley Regional Airport) is also an airport with the lowest amount of operations that is also in our Top 10 Destination Airports with the lowest percent of late arrival operations. However, Chippewa Valley Regional Airport has 10.77% of delay flights.
  • The "delayed" variable is a Boolean, with an unbalance towards the negative (not delayed). This was not a surprise because most airlines report time-related KPIs to the aviation authorities and airports in order to keep their operations.
  • There is a general lower amount of delayed flights in weekends than on weekdays.
  • The amount of delayed flights is the lowest between 1 AM - 4 AM (inclusive) in both weekdays and weekends, up to 100% lower than the mean.
  • The amount of delayed flights per day during September 2007 is the lowest among all the months.
  • All of the Destination Airports of our Worst 10 and Top 10 rankings (based on the percent of late operations) were outliers, following the IQR criteria.
  • All the Flight Numbers of our Worst 11 ranking (with the highest percent of late operations) were outliers, following the IQR criteria.
  • The 10 Origin Airports of our Worst 10 ranking (with the highest percent of late arrivals to their destination) were outliers, following the IQR criteria. 7 Origin Airports of the Top 10 (with the lowest percent of late arrivals to their destination) were also outliers, following the IQR criteria.
  • The distribution of Flights per hour (based on Scheduled Arrival Time) is skewed to the left.
  • When plotted on a log-scale, the distribution of Distance between airports looks roughly normal with a light right skew. We can see there's a steep reduction in the right tail, rather than a smooth ramp down.   • When plotted on a log-scale, the Scheduled Elapsed Time looks roughly normal with a light right skew. We can see that there's a steep reduction in the right tail, rather than a smooth ramp down. Since we have a great amount of outliers with high values, the mean (127) is much greater than the median (110) in the Distribution of Log10 of Scheduled Elapsed Time.

Limitations of this Project:

  • The dataset only included the domestic operations of 21 airlines of United States, so the scope of the analysis is limited by that.
  • Due to the heavy amount of data per year, we decided to only analyze 2007 flight data for this project.
  • Since there were missing values in "CRSElapsedTime" and "ArrDelay" columns, that we could not retrieve, those rows were dropped. As a result, 2.39% of rows were removed from the original dataset.

Other considerations:

  • In the 2007 dataset, there is no information about the airplane model, so the analysis will not include it.
  • Even though the "UniqueCarrier" codes are not explicit enough, we will only fix the names for explanatory graphs since these codes are recognized by IATA.
  • According to U.S.DOT Report of December 2007, data of the merged operations of US Airways (US) and America West Airlines (HP) are combined, and appear only as "US" in this dataset.
  • As of december 2007, the rule required carriers to report on operations to and from the 32 U.S. airports that accounted for at least one percent of the nation's total domestic scheduled-service passenger enplanements. However, all reporting airlines voluntarily provided data for their entire domestic systems, and that information is included in the dataset. The analysis will be based on the total of airports reported.
  • All times are local. A 10:50 a.m. departure from Atlanta is 10:50 a.m. Atlanta time; if that flight arrived in Dallas at 11:45 a.m., that is 11:45 a.m. Dallas time.
  • "On time" means an arrival less than 15 minutes after scheduled arrival time; cancelled and diverted flights are not considered on-time arrivals.
  • According to U.S.DOT Report of December 2007, the Flight Status can be "On Time", "Delayed", "Cancelled" or "Diverted".
  • We decided to drop "DepTime", "CRSDepTime", "ArrTime", "DepDelay", "TailNum", "ActualElapsedTime", "AirTime", "TaxiIn", "TaxiOut", "Cancelled", "CancellationCode", "Diverted", "CarrierDelay", "WeatherDelay", "NASDelay", "SecurityDelay" and "LateAircraftDelay" columns because those are not factors that can generate a flight delay, but information post-delay or post-cancellation or post-diversion.
  • To ease the analysis, the "CRSArrivalTime" column was created considering intervals of 59 minutes, but the label only reflected the hour. P.E: We used the category label of "0 AM" for the "00:00-00:59" range.

Appendix¶

NOTE: The Department of Transportation has screened the reporting carriers' data for completeness and verified all arithmetic data elements computed by the carriers (e.g., length of delay). Individual flight operations records with incorrect calculations, erroneous city-pairs, or missing data elements were rejected and excluded from the dataset; such rejected records accounted for less than 0.01% of the flight operations records submitted. Any errors in the dataset with respect to basic flight data -- non-computed data elements such as flight numbers, scheduled and actual arrival/departure times, days of operation -- are the responsibility of the reporting carrier.
